 ranges from the Victorian fiction of Wilkie Collins, Bram Stoker and Richard Marsh to the music of Tom Waits, world horror cinema and the TV series Doctor Who, this book finds fresh and innovative contexts for the study of Gothic. Combining essays by well-established and emerging scholars, it should appeal to academics and students researching both Gothic literature and culture and the cultural impact of new technologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre)xHistory and criticism. 0aGothic revival (Literature). 4aGothic 2017. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aGothic film.  aGothic literature.  aGothic music.  aGothic.  aHaunting.  aMedia.  aMonstrosity.  aNew media.  aSpectrality.  aTechnology.1 aBaillon, Jean-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotting, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotting, Fred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBronfen, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrophy, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristiansen, Steen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLockwood, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNolan, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuller, Dorothea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoltysik Monnet, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpooner, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https: